name: Kallang Bahru Braised Duck • Kway Chap

reviews.text: The kway chap was below average. The soup was salty without much essence, and the duck drumstick I ordered lacked flavour. The chilli sauce was also much too sour for my liking. On the plus side, the service was prompt, though.

Try duck rice today,order the $4.50 plate, and overall, the food is average because the sambal chill tastes a little bit salty, and rice doesn't taste like yam rice (I'm not sure is the rice suppose to yam rice or not)This is my personal opinion and others have theirs opinion. Lastly, the tray return station is located far away from the dining areas.

13 Apr 25’

Generally, these are the ingredients used for braised duck: Ginger, green onion, cinnamon, star anise, dark soy sauce etc（姜，葱，桂皮，八角, 酱油）

Duck meat higher in fat, including monounsaturated fats, and a good source of protein, iron, and B vitamins (B12 and B3).

According to health experts:
Ginger offers anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties. It can help with digestion, nausea relief, and pain reduction, and may even play a role in managing conditions like osteoarthritis. Additionally, ginger may support cardiovascular health, help with weight management, and potentially offer protection against certain cancers

Cinnamon has antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, antidiabetic, antimicrobial, anticancer, lipid-lowering, and cardiovascular-disease-lowering compound, cinnamon has also been reported to have activities against neurological disorders, such as Parkinson's and Alzheimer's diseases.

According to medicineNet
Star anise has become popular among western medicine practitioners, who value it for its potent antimicrobial properties and therapeutic potential. Studies show that adding this spice to a balanced, nutritious diet can have various positive effects on your health.

Because of all the above, have braised duck meat is one my preferred meat

"Edible but not amazing"

I'm not qualified to comment on braised duck cuisines but my dad has this to say.

We tried dry duck noodles for dine in and ordered a takeaway home to let my dad try. Today he had the rice.

In his words, there is a missing essence of flavours. The rice is not fragrant, the soup is lacking the dong gui ingredient and the duck meat is on the dry side.

A little disclaimer that we are not familiar with the brand, but I want to do them justice by giving some suggestions to make the dish nicer. If it's a franchise, they could listen. But if it's a branch store, it's going to be harder to implement suggestions.
The soup has a bit of herbal taste, but the duck meat taste is quite plain.
